---
import { ChevronDown } from 'lucide-astro';

const faqs = [
  {
    category: "General Questions",
    questions: [
      {
        q: "How much does a concrete foundation cost in Toronto?",
        a: "Foundation costs typically range from $15,000 to $40,000 for a standard residential home. Factors include soil conditions, depth, waterproofing requirements, and accessibility. Poor soil conditions or high water tables can increase costs by 30-50%. We provide free detailed estimates after site inspection."
      },
      {
        q: "How long does it take to build a foundation?",
        a: "A typical residential foundation takes 2-3 weeks: excavation (2-3 days), footings (2 days), walls (3-5 days), waterproofing and backfill (3-4 days), plus curing time. Weather and soil conditions can extend timelines. Shoring requirements add 3-5 days."
      },
      {
        q: "Do you provide warranties on concrete work?",
        a: "Yes, we provide a 25-year structural warranty on foundations, 10 years on waterproofing, 5 years on driveways and patios, and 2 years on decorative finishes. All warranties are fully transferable and backed by our insurance."
      },
      {
        q: "What areas of Toronto do you service?",
        a: "We service all of Toronto including Etobicoke, North York, Scarborough, East York, York, and Downtown. We also work in Mississauga, Brampton, Vaughan, Richmond Hill, Markham, Pickering, and Ajax. Call for other GTA locations."
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    category: "Foundation & Basement",
    questions: [
      {
        q: "What's the difference between dampproofing and waterproofing?",
        a: "Dampproofing (tar coating) resists moisture but not water pressure - suitable for well-drained sites. Waterproofing (membrane systems) resists hydrostatic pressure - required for high water tables or poor drainage. Toronto's clay soils often require full waterproofing for basement protection."
      },
      {
        q: "How deep do foundations need to be in Toronto?",
        a: "Foundations must extend below the frost line - 1.2m (4 feet) minimum in Toronto for heated buildings. Unheated structures require 1.5m depth. Frost-protected shallow foundations are possible with proper insulation design."
      },
      {
        q: "Can you repair a cracked foundation?",
        a: "Yes, most foundation cracks can be repaired. Hairline cracks: epoxy injection ($500-1,500). Structural cracks: may require underpinning or reinforcement ($5,000-20,000). We assess all cracks free and recommend appropriate solutions."
      },
      {
        q: "Do I need a permit for foundation work?",
        a: "Yes, all foundation work requires a building permit in Toronto. New foundations, underpinning, waterproofing, and structural repairs all need permits. We handle all permit applications and inspections as part of our service."
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    category: "Driveways & Exterior",
    questions: [
      {
        q: "How thick should a concrete driveway be?",
        a: "Residential driveways should be 100-150mm (4-6\") thick. We recommend 150mm for Toronto's freeze-thaw cycles. Always use 32 MPa concrete with 5-8% air entrainment for salt resistance. Proper base preparation is critical - 150mm compacted granular minimum."
      },
      {
        q: "When can I drive on new concrete?",
        a: "Light foot traffic: 24-48 hours. Cars: 7 days minimum. Heavy vehicles: 28 days. Avoid de-icing salts for the first winter. Apply sealer after 30 days for maximum protection. Early loading causes permanent damage."
      },
      {
        q: "Why did my driveway crack?",
        a: "Common causes: inadequate base preparation, no control joints, too much water in mix, rapid drying, early salt exposure, or tree roots. Proper installation includes control joints every 3m, proper curing, and sealed edges."
      },
      {
        q: "How long do concrete driveways last?",
        a: "Properly installed concrete driveways last 25-30 years in Toronto. Key factors: proper drainage, air entrainment, sealing, avoiding salt first year, and resealing every 3-5 years. Poor installation fails in 5-10 years."
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    category: "Concrete Quality & Testing",
    questions: [
      {
        q: "What strength concrete do I need?",
        a: "Depends on application: Interior footings/walls: 15-20 MPa. Basement slabs: 20-25 MPa. Garage slabs: 32 MPa with air. Driveways/exterior: 32 MPa with 5-8% air. We specify correct mix for each application."
      },
      {
        q: "What is air-entrained concrete?",
        a: "Air entrainment adds microscopic air bubbles (5-8%) that allow water to expand when freezing without damaging concrete. Required for all exterior concrete in Toronto. Adds ~$5/m³ but prevents scaling and spalling."
      },
      {
        q: "How do you test concrete quality?",
        a: "We perform slump tests (workability), air content tests (freeze protection), and cast cylinders for compression testing at 7 and 28 days. All testing follows CSA standards. Test reports provided for warranty."
      },
      {
        q: "Can you pour concrete in winter?",
        a: "Yes, with precautions. Concrete must be kept above 10°C for 72 hours minimum. We use heated concrete, insulation blankets, and sometimes temporary shelters. Winter pours cost 15-25% more but are safe when done properly."
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    category: "Costs & Process",
    questions: [
      {
        q: "What factors affect concrete pricing?",
        a: "Main factors: concrete strength and type, quantity (small loads cost more per m³), accessibility (pumping adds $800-1,500), season (winter adds 15-25%), site conditions (shoring/dewatering), and finishing requirements."
      },
      {
        q: "Do you require deposits?",
        a: "Yes, typically 30% upon signing, 40% when we start, 30% upon completion. Foundation projects may have progress payments. All deposits go into trust account. Never pay 100% upfront to any contractor."
      },
      {
        q: "How do I prepare for concrete work?",
        a: "Clear access paths, remove vehicles, protect landscaping, notify neighbors, arrange utility locates (we handle this), and ensure water access. For interior work, clear basement and protect belongings from dust."
      },
      {
        q: "What happens if it rains?",
        a: "Light rain during pour: we continue with covers ready. Heavy rain: we postpone. Fresh concrete damaged by rain must be removed. Rain after finishing is protected with plastic. Weather delays don't change price."
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    category: "Problems & Solutions",
    questions: [
      {
        q: "My basement leaks - what are my options?",
        a: "Interior: crack injection, interior drainage system, sump pump ($3,000-8,000). Exterior: excavate and waterproof properly ($15,000-30,000). Exterior solutions are permanent but cost more. We assess free and recommend best approach."
      },
      {
        q: "Can you match existing concrete color?",
        a: "Exact matching is impossible - concrete color varies with age, weather, and original mix. We can get close with stains or overlays. For visible areas, consider decorative finishes or complete replacement for uniform appearance."
      },
      {
        q: "What causes concrete scaling/spalling?",
        a: "Usually from: no air entrainment, poor curing, early salt exposure, or high water content. Surface repairs are temporary. Severe scaling requires overlay or replacement. Prevention is key - proper mix and curing."
      },
      {
        q: "How do you fix sinking concrete?",
        a: "Options: Mudjacking (pump grout underneath): $500-2,000 per slab. Polyurethane injection: $800-3,000. Complete replacement: $3,000-8,000. Choice depends on cause of sinking and slab condition."
      }
    ]
  }
];
---

<section id="faq" class="py-16 bg-gray-50">
  <div class="container mx-auto px-4">
    <div class="text-center mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">
        Frequently Asked Questions
      </h2>
      <p class="text-xl text-gray-600 max-w-3xl mx-auto">
        39 years of experience answering Toronto's concrete questions
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto">
      {faqs.map((category) => (
        <div class="mb-8">
          <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4 pb-2 border-b-2 border-red-600">
            {category.category}
          </h3>
          <div class="space-y-4">
            {category.questions.map((faq, index) => (
              <details class="group bg-white rounded-lg shadow-sm border border-gray-200 hover:shadow-md transition-shadow">
                <summary class="flex items-center justify-between p-6 cursor-pointer list-none">
                  <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900 pr-4">
                    {faq.q}
                  </h4>
                  <ChevronDown class="w-5 h-5 text-gray-500 group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0" />
                </summary>
                <div class="px-6 pb-6">
                  <p class="text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
                    {faq.a}
                  </p>
                </div>
              </details>
            ))}
          </div>
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>

    <div class="mt-12 text-center">
      <p class="text-gray-600 mb-6">
        Can't find your answer? We're here to help.
      </p>
      <div class="flex flex-col sm:flex-row gap-4 justify-center">
        <a href="tel:4375450067" class="inline-block px-8 py-3 bg-red-600 text-white rounded-lg font-semibold hover:bg-red-700 transition-colors">
          Call: (437) 545-0067
        </a>
        <a href="/contact" class="inline-block px-8 py-3 bg-white text-gray-900 border-2 border-gray-300 rounded-lg font-semibold hover:bg-gray-50 transition-colors">
          Send Message
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<style>
  details summary::-webkit-details-marker {
    display: none;
  }
  
  details summary::marker {
    display: none;
  }
</style>